## Techniques for GANs

### 1. Abstract

We present a variety of new architectural features and training procedures that we
apply to the GANs framework

### 2. Introduction

GANs are based on game theory, training GANs requires finding a **Nash equil of a non-convex game with continuous, high dim params**. When used to seek for a Nash equilibrium, these algorithms may fail to converge

### 3. Converging GAN

Training GANs is to find a Nash equil, where the cost func are non-convex, the params are continuous and high-dim

##### Feature matching

In the beginning of training, $G$ only gives out poor fake samples, so the $D(x)$ would be much close to 0 and therefore lead $L_{GD}$ to be infinite and gredient unstable.

Letting $f(x)$ denote activations on an layer of the $D$, our new objective for $G$ is:
$$
||E_{x\sim p_{data}}f(x)-E_{z\sim p_z(z)}f(G(Z))||^2
$$
Empirical results indicate that feature matching is effective where regular GAN unstable.

##### Minibatch discrimination

minibatch discrimination is a strategy to avoid “ $G$ collapsing”  . 

it t looks at multiple examples in combination, rather than in isolation, and it states as follows:
$$
M_{i,b}=f(x_i) \times T\;\;\;\;\;\;\text{T is a weight mat}    \\
c_b(x_i,x_j)=\exp(-|| M_{i,b}-M_{j,b} ||)_{L_1} \\
o(x_i)_b=\sum_{j=1}^nc_b(x_i,x_j)\in R\\
o(x_i)=[o(x_i)_1,o(x_i)_2,\cdots,o(x_i)_n]
$$
And it looks like in graph as follows:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) 

Next, we concatenate the output $o(x_i)$  with $f(x_i)$ , and we feed it into the next layer of $D$. Samples from generator and training data are computing separately. 

The $D$ is therefore able to use the other examples in the minibatch as side information. 

##### Historical averaging

Modifying player’s cost to include a term:
$$
|| \theta-\frac{1}{t}\sum_{i=1}^t\theta[i]\; ||^2
$$
where $θ[i]$ is the value of the parameters at past time $i$. 

##### One-sided label smoothin

Label smoothing replaces the 0 and 1 targets for a classifier with smoothed values, like $0.9-1$ or $0-0.1$.

We smooth only the positive labels to $α$, leaving negative labels set to 0.

### 4. Conclusion

GANs are a promising class of generative models that has so far been held back by unstable training and by the lack of a proper evaluation metric. 

This work presents partial solutions to both of these problems
